Rating: 4
I've made this a few times for cocktail parties and it's always a hit. I've also been asked for the recipe more than once. I do not roll the tenderloin, as I think that makes it harder to bite off. I simply lay it across the bread. I also have a hard time finding decent Rye bread for the toasts, so I frequently use good quality french bread slices. In a pinch (logistical or economical) I've used proscuitto instead of tenderloin. But you must use the Parma prosciutto. Otherwise, don't bother.

Rating: 4
I love this recipe and make it often! In a pinch I will use jarred artichoke bruschetta from Trader Joes. The key here is to use a GOOD piece of tenderloin (yes, it'll cost you 20 bucks but it is worth it), lots of kosher salt and fresh ground pepper, sear it on the grill a minute or 2 a side then finish indirectly, 3 - 4 minutes a side (you want it RARE so it melts in your mouth!) which can be done a day in advance. Serve room temp.

